04731nam a22006735i 9780674038035DE-B159720220131112047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220131t20222002mau    fo  d z      eng d  a97806740380357 a10.4159/97806740380352doi  a(DE-B1597)571808  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 4aE184.A1 ǂb G94 2003eb 7aPOL0040002bisacsh04a305.81 aGuinier, Lani, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Miner’s Canary :bEnlisting Race, Resisting Power, Transforming Democracy /cLani Guinier, Gerald Torres. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2022] 4c©2002  a1 online resource (400 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aThe Nathan I. Huggins Lectures00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPrologue -- t1. Political Race and Magical Realism -- t2. A Critique of Colorblindness -- t3. Race as a Political Space -- t4. Rethinking Conventions of Zero-Sum Power -- t5. Enlisting Race to Resist Hierarchy -- t6. The Problem Democracy Is Supposed to Solve -- t7. Whiteness of a Different Color? -- t8. Watching the Canary -- tNotes -- tAcknowledgments -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aLike the canaries that alerted miners to a poisonous atmosphere, issues of race point to underlying problems in society that ultimately affect everyone, not just minorities. Addressing these issues is essential. Ignoring racial differences--race blindness--has failed. Focusing on individual achievement has diverted us from tackling pervasive inequalities. Now, in a powerful and challenging book, Lani Guinier and Gerald Torres propose a radical new way to confront race in the twenty-first century. Given the complex relationship between race and power in America, engaging race means engaging standard winner-take-all hierarchies of power as well. Terming their concept "political race," Guinier and Torres call for the building of grass-roots, cross-racial coalitions to remake those structures of power by fostering public participation in politics and reforming the process of democracy. Their illuminating and moving stories of political race in action include the coalition of Hispanic and black leaders who devised the Texas Ten Percent Plan to establish equitable state college admissions criteria, and the struggle of black workers in North Carolina for fair working conditions that drew on the strength and won the support of the entire local community. The aim of political race is not merely to remedy racial injustices, but to create truly participatory democracy, where people of all races feel empowered to effect changes that will improve conditions for everyone. In a book that is ultimately not only aspirational but inspirational, Guinier and Torres envision a social justice movement that could transform the nature of democracy in America.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Civil Rights.2bisacsh1 aTorres, Gerald, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013 (Canada)z978311075606708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHarvard University Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044220540uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/9780674038035zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674038035423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780674038035/original  a978-3-11-044220-5  Harvard University Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-075606-7  HUP eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013 (Canada)b2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGB